sentences: Eleanor Deanne Therese Alberga  (born 1949) is a Jamaican contemporary music composer who lives and works in the United Kingdom.

She studied music at Jamaica School of Music and in 1970 she won the biennial West Indian Associated Board Scholarship which allowed her to study at the Royal Academy of Music in London, where one of her teachers was Richard Stoker.
In 2001 she ended her career as a performer to concentrate full-time on composition and was awarded a NESTA Fellowship.
She married violinist Thomas Bowes in 1992 and performs with him in a duo called Double Exposure.
He was the premiere soloist for both of her Violin Concertos (2001 and 2019).
Alberga was appointed Officer of the Order of the British Empire (OBE) in the 2021 Birthday Honours for services to music.
Some of the piano music in particular, such as the Jamaican Medley (1983), Hill and Gully Ride (1990) and 3 Day Mix (1991), draw on her Jamaican background in their use of colour and cross-rhythms.

Later pieces show an increasing use of dissonance as in her three string quartets (1993, 1994 and 2001) which have been recorded by Ensemble Arcadiana.

A later recording by the Taliesin Orchestra in 2011 featured Danny DeVito, Griff Rhys Jones and Joanna Lumley as the narrators.
It opened at the Royal Opera House Linbury Studio in 2009 before touring England and Wales.
The choral work Arise, Athena!, setting her own text, was written to open the last night of the BBC Proms in 2015.
